Subject: [ARCHEOLOGY] clk: sunxi-ng: ccu_common: Replace ktime-dependent lock
 wait loop with udelay (#10119)

> X-Git-Archeology: > recovered message: > The Allwinner sunxi-ng clock control unit (CCU) driver utilizes
> X-Git-Archeology: > recovered message: > readl_relaxed_poll_timeout_atomic() inside ccu_helper_wait_for_lock()
> X-Git-Archeology: > recovered message: > to wait for PLLs to lock. This timeout loop relies internally on ktime_get()
> X-Git-Archeology: > recovered message: > and timekeeping APIs.
> X-Git-Archeology: > recovered message: > During early boot or clock transitions (such as CPUfreq DVFS scaling),
> X-Git-Archeology: > recovered message: > the system's clock sources and timekeeping may be unstable or temporarily
> X-Git-Archeology: > recovered message: > suspended. This causes ktime_get() to fail to increment or return invalid
> X-Git-Archeology: > recovered message: > readings, turning the timeout calculation into an infinite busy-wait loop
> X-Git-Archeology: > recovered message: > and triggering critical RCU stalls / kernel lockups.
> X-Git-Archeology: > recovered message: > Decouple the PLL lock wait loop from the timekeeping framework by replacing
> X-Git-Archeology: > recovered message: > the poll timeout loop with a robust, timekeeping-independent iteration loop
> X-Git-Archeology: > recovered message: > utilizing udelay(1) (up to 100,000 iterations / 100ms timeout limit). This
> X-Git-Archeology: > recovered message: > avoids timekeeping dependencies during sensitive frequency scaling operations
> X-Git-Archeology: > recovered message: > and prevents infinite CPU lockups when timer interrupts are suspended.
